<section xml:id="sec-intervals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Intervals</title>

  <p>We often want to talk about all the points to the left of a given point, to the right of a given point, or in between two points. These are called <term>intervals</term>.</p>

  <p>For convenience, we will talk about the real numbers corresponding to the points of an interval rather than the points of the interval itself. Notice that it can get convoluted when we are precise by explicitly keeping the points and their corresponding real numbers separate in how we write and speak. It is common practice to just <em>identify</em> the point with its corresponding number and talk about the real number as if it were a point. So instead of talking about the point corresponding to the real number <m>x</m>, we will often just refer to the "point" <m>x</m> instead.</p>

  <p>There are two key distinguishing properties for intervals: (1) finite vs. infinite and (2) open vs. closed.</p>

  <p>Our first type of intervals will be the <term>infinite</term> ones. These are the intervals that consist of all the points to the left or all the points to the right of a given point.  On the other hand, we can have range of values between two given values <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>; in that case we say we have a <term>finite</term> interval.</p>
  
  <p>Should boundary values of our interval be included? It depends on the situation. If we want to include the boundary of our interval, then we use the word <em>closed</em>. If we want to exclude the boundaries of our interval, the we use the word <em>open</em>. If we include one but not the other of our boundary points, we say the interval is <term>half-open/half-closed</term>.</p>

  <p>We described the different types of intervals above in words. We could also use inequalities (using <m>\leq</m> and <m>\geq</m> symbols) and what is called <em>set builder notation</em>. There is another notation that is simpler (but can be confusing when we get to two-dimensional spaces). We call this simpler notation <term>interval notation</term>, which uses just parentheses ( and ) and brackets [ and ]. Here are eight types of intervals and how they are expressed in the various kinds of notation, including interval notation:</p>

  <table>
