<p>Applications of Intervals</p>

  <p>So why do we care so much about intervals? We will pretty frequently want to describe some subset of the real number line as a solution set to problems, or as a way to communicate what values work for a formula or algorithm.</p>

  <p>For example, consider the function <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>. From prerequisite courses, we know that you can't take the square root of a negative. Conversely, the only values of <m>x</m> that make sense to take a square root of are zero and any positive number. How can we express "zero and any positive number" using symbols? Notice that the positive numbers are the numbers to the right of zero. Thus we are talking about the interval of numbers including zero and all numbers to its right. We can express this in interval notation as <m>[0,\infty)</m>. That's a lot shorter than saying "zero and any positive number"!</p>

  <p>Intervals are also the natural way to give the solutions for <em>inequalities</em> such as <m>5x-3\geq x+5</m> or <m>|2x-1|\gt 2</m>. Let's solve these equations, but before we do that, let's do a quick refresher about how to deal with inequalities:</p>

<theorem>
    <title>Properties of Inequalities</title>
  <statement>
      <p>Addition Property of Inequalities
        <ul>
          <li>If <m>a&lt;b</m>, then <m>a+c&lt; b+c</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>a\leq b</m>, then <m>a+c\leq b+c</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>a&gt;b</m>, then <m>a+c&gt; b+c</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>a\geq b</m>, then <m>a+c\geq b+c</m>.</li>         
        </ul>
      In other words, if you add the same value to both sides of a true inequality, the inequality remains true.
      </p>
      <p>Multiplication Property of Inequalities
        <ul>
          <li>If <m>a&lt;b</m> and <m>c\gt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c&lt; b\cdot c</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>a\leq b</m> and <m>c\gt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c\leq b\cdot c</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>a&gt;b</m> and <m>c\gt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c&gt; b\cdot c</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>a\geq b</m> and <m>c\gt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c\geq b\cdot c</m>.</li>         
        </ul>
      In other words, if you multiply the same positive value to both sides of a true inequality, the inequality remains true.
      <ul>
        <li>If <m>a&lt;b</m> and <m>c\lt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c&gt; b\cdot c</m>.</li>
        <li>If <m>a\leq b</m> and <m>c\lt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c\geq b\cdot c</m>.</li>
        <li>If <m>a&gt;b</m> and <m>c\lt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c&lt; b\cdot c</m>.</li>
        <li>If <m>a\geq b</m> and <m>c\lt 0</m>, then <m>a\cdot c\leq b\cdot c</m>.</li>         
      </ul>
      In other words, if you multiply the same negative value to both sides of a true inequality, the inequality must be "reversed" to remain true.
      </p>
      <p>Absolute Value and Inequalities:
        <ul>
          <li>If <m>|x|\lt a</m>, then <m>x\lt a</m> <em>and</em> <m>x\gt -a</m>, or in other words, <m>-a\lt x\lt a</m> or <m>x</m> can be any value in the interval <m>(-a,a)</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>|x|\leq a</m>, then <m>x\leq a</m> <em>and</em> <m>x\geq -a</m>, or in other words, <m>-a\leq x\leq a</m> or <m>x</m> can be any value in the interval <m>[-a,a]</m>.</li>
          <li>If <m>|x|\gt a</m>, then <m>x\gt a</m> <em>or</em> <m>x\lt -a</m>, or in other words, <m>x</m> can be any value in the interval <m>(-\infty,-a)</m> or in the interval <m>(a,\infty)</m>.</li>   
          <li>If <m>|x|\geq a</m>, then <m>x\geq a</m> <em>or</em> <m>x\leq -a</m>, or in other words, <m>x</m> can be any value in the interval <m>(-\infty,-a]</m> or in the interval <m>[a,\infty)</m>.</li>  
        </ul></p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>Note: when we want to put two disjoint intervals together into a single answer, such as how with <m>|x|\gt 2</m> we know that <m>x</m> can be any number in the interval <m>(-\infty, -2)</m> or in the interval <m>(2,\infty)</m>, we use the <m>\cup</m> symbol to join them: <m>(-\infty, -2)\cup (2,\infty).</m></p>

<example>
  <title>Solving a Linear Inequality</title>
  <statement>
      <p>Solve <m>5x-3\geq x+5</m>. Express the solutions of the following inequalities in interval notation and shade the region of a number line that corresponds to the solutions.</p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
      <p>Strategy: if we can get our equation to look like <m>x\lt a</m>, <m>x\leq a</m>, <m>x\gt a</m>, or <m>x\geq a</m>, then we are done! Let's use properties of inequalities to do that. It should remind you of how we usually solve <em>linear</em> equations.
      <md>
        <mrow>5x-3 \amp\geq x+5</mrow>
        <mrow>5x-3+3 \amp\geq x+5+3 </mrow>
        <mrow>5x \amp\geq x+8 </mrow>
        <mrow>5x-x \amp\geq x+8 - x </mrow>
        <mrow>4x \amp\geq 8 </mrow>
        <mrow>x \amp\geq 2.</mrow>
      </md></p>
      <p>Thus our solution includes all real numbers greater than or equal to <m>2</m>. In interval notation, we would write <m>[2,\infty).</m></p>
      <p>We can graph the solution on a number line as follows. Since <m>2</m> is included, we used a filled circle for that boundary point.</p>
      <image source="/img/0124_01.png"></image>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Solving an Inequality Involving Absolute Value</title>
  <statement>
   <p>Solve <m>|2x-1|\gt 2</m>. Express the solutions of the following inequalities in interval notation and shade the region of a number line that corresponds to the solutions.</p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
      <p>Strategy: We will use what we know about absolute value and inequalities to get us going. We know that any <m>x</m> that solves <m>2x-1\gt 2</m> or that solves <m>2x-1\lt -2</m> will be a solution to our original problem.</p>
      <p>First, 
      <md> 
        <mrow>2x-1 \amp\gt 2 </mrow>
        <mrow>2x \amp\gt 3 </mrow>
        <mrow>x \amp\gt \frac{3}{2}.</mrow>
      </md></p>
      <p>Second, 
        <md> 
          <mrow>2x-1 \amp\lt -2 </mrow>
          <mrow>2x \amp\lt -1 </mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp\lt -\frac{1}{2}.</mrow>
        </md></p>
      <p>Thus our solution includes all real numbers greater than or equal to <m>\frac{3}{2}</m> and all real numbers less than or equal to <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>. In interval notation, we would write <m>\left(-\infty,-\frac{1}{2}\right)\cup\left(\frac{3}{2},\infty\right).</m></p>
      <p>We can graph the solution on a number line as follows. Since <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>\frac{3}{2}</m> are not solutions, we use open circles at those boundary points.</p>
      <image source="/img/0124_02.png"></image>
  </solution>
</example>

